07567nam a22009255i 9780824861896DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20072007hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248618967 a10.1515/97808248618962doi  a(DE-B1597)484683  a(OCoLC)1024061760  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aBR1325b.C525 2006eb 7aREL0840002bisacsh04a275.1922200aChristianity in Korea /ced. by Timothy S. Lee, Robert E. Buswell. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tI. Overview -- t1. A Quarter-Millennium of Christianity in Korea -- tII. The Beginnings of Christianity in Korea -- t2. Human Relations as Expressed in Vernacular Catholic Writings of the Late Chosŏn Dynasty; translated by Timothy S. Lee -- t3. Kollumba Kang Wansuk, an Early Catholic Activist and Martyr -- t4. Chinese Protestant Literature and Early Korean Protestantism -- tIII. Christianity, Nationalism, and Japanese Colonialism -- t5. Church and State Relations in the Japanese Colonial Period -- t6. Cradle of the Convenant: Ahn Changho and the Christian Roots of the Korean Constitution -- t7. Preaching the Apocalypse in Colonial Korea -- t8. Mothers, Daughters, Biblewomen, and Sisters -- tIV. Christianity and the Struggles for Democracy and Reunification -- t9. Carrying the Torch in the Darkest Hours: The Sociopolitical Origins of Minjung Protestant Movements -- t10. Minjung Theology’s Biblical Hermeneutics: An Examination of Minjung Theology’s Appropriation of the Exodus Account -- t11. Korean Protestants and the Reunification Movement; Translated by Timothy S. Lee -- tThe Division and Reunification of a Nation -- tV. Growth and Challenges -- t13. Sibling Rivalry in Twentieth-Century Korea: Comparative Growth Rates of Catholic and Protestant Communities -- t14. Modernization and the Explosive Growth and Decline of Korean Protestant Religiosity -- t15. Beleaguered Success -- t16. In Search of Healing -- t17. The Christian-Buddhist Encounter in Korea -- tA Select Bibliography for the Study of Korean Christianity -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite the significance of Korea in world Christianity and the crucial role Christianity plays in contemporary Korean religious life, the tradition has been little studied in the West. Christianity in Korea seeks to fill this lacuna by providing a wide-ranging overview of the growth and development of Korean Christianity and the implications that development has had for Korean politics, interreligious dialogue, and gender and social issues. The volume begins with an accessibly written overview that traces in broad outline the history and development of Christianity on the peninsula. This is followed by chapters on broad themes, such as the survival of early Korean Catholics in a Neo-Confucian society, relations between Christian churches and colonial authorities during the Japanese occupation, premillennialism, and the theological significance of the division and prospective reunification of Korea. Others look in more detail at individuals and movements, including the story of the female martyr Kollumba Kang Wansuk; the influence of Presbyterianism on the renowned nationalist Ahn Changho; the sociopolitical and theological background of the Minjung Protestant Movement; and the success and challenges of Evangelical Protestantism in Korea. The book concludes with a discussion of how best to encourage a rapprochement between Buddhism and Christianity in Korea.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aChristianityzKorea. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & St